.SH "NAME"
HTTP::Session2::ServerStore \- Session store
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module is a part of HTTP::Session2 library.
This module saves the session data on server side storage.
.SH "CONSTRUCTOR PARAMETERS"
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR PARAMETERS"
.IP "store: Object, optional" 4
.IX Item "store: Object, optional"
The storage object. You need to set 'store' or 'get_store'.
.IP "get_store : CodeRef,  optional" 4
.IX Item "get_store : CodeRef,  optional"
Callback function to get the storage object.
.Sp
The storage object must have following 3 methods.
.RS 4
.ie n .IP "$cache\->get($key:Str)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$cache\fR\->get($key:Str)" 4
.IX Item "$cache->get($key:Str)"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP "$cache\->set($key:Str, $value:Serializable)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$cache\fR\->set($key:Str, \f(CW$value:Serializable\fR)" 4
.IX Item "$cache->set($key:Str, $value:Serializable)"
.ie n .IP "$cache\->remove($key:Str)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$cache\fR\->remove($key:Str)" 4
.IX Item "$cache->remove($key:Str)"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
And, cache object should be serialize/deserialize the data automatically.
.Sp
\&\s-1CHI\s0 supports all things. You can use any \s-1CHI\s0 drivers.
.Sp
But, I recommend to use \f(CW\*(C`Cache::Memcached::Fast\*(C'\fR.
.RE
